<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin: NATO Must Strike To Maintain `Credibility' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2002180594 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1700 
GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2002180594 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has said that even if 
only one weapon remains outside Sarajevo, NATO must implement 
its decision to intervene if it wants to maintain its 
respectability and credibility. 
  Replying to questions by our correspondent, Cetin pointed 
out 
that all weapons outside Sarajevo must be under UN control 
within the next few hours. Otherwise, he said, NATO must 
intervene. 
  Cetin said he had a telephone conversation with Bosnian 
President Alija Izetbegovic this afternoon. He pointed out that 
20 percent of the Serbs' heavy weapons have not been placed 
under UN control yet, and that there are reports that some of 
the weapons are being taken to residential areas. The latter 
constitute a potential danger, Cetin said, and must be placed 
under UN control with the other weapons. 
  Cetin recalled that Turkey, a NATO member, has been saying 
for the past 22 months that a limited air operation would be a 
first step toward the solution of the problem. The latest 
developments justify our position, he stressed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

