<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Denktas Arrives in Ankara To Discuss Cyprus Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2102160494 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1450 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2102160494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb 21 (AA) -- President Rauf Denktas of 
the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus [TRNC] who arrived in 
Ankara on Monday [21 February] for a series of talks with high 
level Turkish officials said 'we will discuss confidence 
building measures with Ankara'. 
  Denktas is accompanied by Prime Minister Hakki Atun, 
Minister 
for State and Deputy Prime Minister Ozker Ozgur, Minister for 
Foreign Affairs and Defense Atay Ahmet Rasit. 
  Denktas said during his first official visit to Turkey with 
the new coalition government they will coordinate efforts as the 
new rounds of Cyprus talks which are scheduled to take place 
under the auspices of the United Nations. 
  TRNC president said the talks in Ankara will focus on the 
package of 'confidence building measures,' adding 'we will 
inform the Turkish Government about our thoughts on the 
measures'. 
  He said TRNC is ready to say 'yes' to a satisfactory, 
balanced and stable solution to the Cyprus problem. 
  Denktas said a positive result could only be taken if the 
Greek Cypriots show the same good will. 
  U.N.-sponsored intercommunal talks on Cyprus were 
interrupted 
last July. 
  Cyprus has been practically divided since 1974 when Turkey 
conducted a peace operation to the island following a 
Greek-backed coup which attempted to annex the island to Greece 
and to annihilate its Turkish Cypriot population. 
  The TRNC came to existence in 1983. 
  Denktas as well as Prime Minister Atun and those 
accompanying 
them will return to Cyprus on Wednesday after their talks in 
Ankara. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

