<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EC Warns Greece on Illegality of FYROM Blockade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1802161994 Paris AFP in English 1614 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU1802161994 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb 18 (AFP) -- The European Community 
warned Friday [18 February] it could issue a legal challenge 
over Greece's trade embargo of Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia--FYROM], an EC official said, raising the 
prospect of the current EC president being dragged into court by 
its Community partners. 
  The controversial Greek move will be discussed by EC foreign 
ministers at their meeting Monday, the European Commission 
spokesman said. 
  Experts at the executive EC Commission are to study the 
impact of the Greek decision, which could breach Community laws 
on free trade with a third state. 
  Belgian Foreign Minister Willy Claes, attending a meeting of 
the EC "troika" of foreign ministers of past, present and future 
presidency incumbents in Athens, said the blockade was 
"naturally in contradiction" with the Maastricht Treaty on 
European Union. 
  Greek European Affairs Minister Theodoros Pangalos swiftly 
rejected the move, saying his government's decision "conformed 
to European law." 
  German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel, also attending, 
earlier 
demanded that Greece immediately lift its trade embargo of its 
land-locked neighbour, and issued a sharp attack on Athens' 
"extraordinary" decision. 

</TEXT>

