<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Clinton Telephones Ciller To Discuss Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1802194494 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 1800 
GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA1802194494 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over stills of Prime Minister Tansu </F>
ciller and U.S. President Bill Clinton] 
  [Text] U.S. President Bill Clinton telephoned Prime 
Minister Tansu Ciller this afternoon and conversed with her for 
half an hour on developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  A statement issued by the Prime Minister's Press Center 
stated: The telephone conversation, which took place while a 
meeting on the struggle against terrorism was under way at the 
presidential palace, lasted approximately 30 minutes. The 
developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina were discussed during the 
conversation. In a statement after her conversation with 
Clinton, Ciller said: Both Mr. Clinton and I are hopeful about 
developments in Bosnia-Herzegovina following the NATO decision 
on the subject. 
  The statement added: Mr. Clinton also sent a letter to 
Ciller. In his letter on Bosnia-Herzegovina, which was relayed 
to the prime minister by the U.S. ambassador to Ankara, Clinton 
thanked Ciller for telephoning him before her departure for 
Sarajevo. Clinton described Ciller's visit to Sarajevo, 
accompanied by Pakistani Prime Minister Bhutto, as courageous 
and expressed his admiration. Clinton also stressed that he 
fully shares Ciller's feelings with regard to the inhuman attack 
launched against innocent people in Sarajevo on 5 February. 

</TEXT>

