<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EC Commission: Greek Embargo on FYROM Violates Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2202172894 Paris AFP in English 1710 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2202172894 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb 22 (AFP) - The EC's executive 
Commission sent a letter to the Greek Government on Tuesday [22 
February], demanding an explanation for its recent trade embargo 
on the Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia, EC officials said. 
  The Commission said it was very concerned about the step, 
which it argued went against European law. 
  Greece blocked access to its northern port of Salonika to 
its 
neighbouring state last week, accusing it of usurping the name 
Macedonia and having territorial designs on the northern Greek 
province of the same name. 
  Under EC law, the unilateral sanctions would be illegal 
unless Greece could prove the action was justified by a threat 
to public order and safety. 
  The Commission cited Article 169 of the European Union 
Treaty, which says that if the Commission feels a member state 
has not met its obligations, it has the right to issue a 
decision on the matter after asking the member state concerned 
to contribute its observations. 
  If the member state does not comply with the decision in the 
period specified by the Commission, the latter can have recourse 
to the European Court of Justice, according to the treaty. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

