<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Constitution Adopted, Opposition Remains Critical </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1802153394 Brussels L'ECHO in French 18 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BR1802153394 </F>
<F P=104>  Brussels L'ECHO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "The King Has Approved the </F>
Constitution"] 
  [Text] On Thursday [17 February] in Brussels the presidents 
of the Chamber of Deputies and the Senate, the government, and 
the King signed the new constitutional text, drawn up in the 
wake of the latest institutional changes. 
  This text is a more readable, coordinated, and renumbered 
version of the old constitutional texts and includes the changes 
introduced by the St. Michel agreements. It was adopted 
definitively by the Senate on 3 February and issued in a special 
edition of the MONITEUR, published yesterday afternoon. Liberal 
MPs, both French-speaking and Flemish-speaking, did not take 
part in the ceremonies surrounding the signature of the new text. 
  For the PRL [Republican Party of Liberty]-FDF [Radical 
Liberal Party--Democratic Front of Brussels French speakers] 
Federation, yesterday was a "black day for Belgium and a day of 
mourning for French speakers." Their MPs point out in 
particular that, in their eyes, the new institutions will 
encourage the separatist current in Flanders and organize the 
division of the French speakers. 

</TEXT>

