<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Belgium </F>
<H3> <TI>   Alleged Arms Trafficking Through Antwerp Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR1802153294 Antwerp GAZET VAN ANTWERPEN in Dutch 18 Feb 94 
p 6 </F>

<F P=103> BR1802153294 </F>
<F P=104>  Antwerp GAZET VAN ANTWERPEN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Arms for FIS Via Antwerp?"] </F>
  [Text] Antwerp -- An Algerian freighter, which recently put 
into port in Algiers with a cargo of arms on board, spent a few 
days last month in the port of Antwerp. In reaction to reports 
in the Algerian press that the weapons were possibly loaded in 
Antwerp, sources at the port confirmed yesterday evening that 
the 5,331-tonne El Djorf called at Antwerp on 14 January en 
route from Hamburg and left on 20 January. 
  The Algerian press agency, APS, had reported -- citing 
newspapers in Algiers -- that automatic guns, shotguns, and 
ammunition were found on board and were were presumably destined 
for extremist Muslims in the FIS [Islamic Salvation Front]. 
Several crew members were detained. 
  According to those arrested, the weapons were "accidentally" 
loaded in Antwerp instead of Hamburg. According to the Algerian 
Government, Germany has become the crossroads for arms smuggling 
from Iranian and Pakistani organizations to Muslim extremists. 
There are currently a number of FIS leaders in Germany, 
including spokesman Rabah Kebir, as well as Okba, Salman, and 
Ikbal Madan, the sons of jailed FIS leader Sheik Abassi Madani. 

</TEXT>

