<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kooijmans Supports FYROM's Crvenkovski </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2202152194 Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT in Dutch 22 Feb 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR2202152194 </F>
<F P=104>  Amsterdam DE VOLKSKRANT </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Kooijmans Supports Macedonian </F>
Colleague Regarding Embargo"] 
  [Excerpts] The Hague -- Macedonian Foreign Minister Stevo 
Crvenkovski and his Netherlands counterpart, Pieter Kooijmans, 
agreed that the trade embargo imposed on Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] by Greece last week is 
outrageous. The two ministers consider the Greek move to be 
both politically reprehensible and in contravention of Community 
law within the European Union. This was learned Monday [21 
February] during an official visit to The Hague by the FYROM 
minister. 
  The Netherlands is the first member state of the European 
Union to receive a member of the FYROM Government on an official 
visit. The FYROM is appreciative of the Dutch support it 
received in connection with rescheduling its debt with the World 
Bank. 
  During the meeting with Minister Kooijmans, Crvenkovski 
emphasized that his government is prepared to resume 
negotiations with Greece aimed at eliminating contentious 
issues, such as the name and flag of the FYROM. [passage 
omitted] 
  According to a spokesman at the Foreign Ministry, Kooijmans 
and Crvenkovski also exchanged views on the situation of the 
Albanian minority in the FYROM, and on the guarantees of 
equality for all inhabitants of the FYROM which are enshrined in 
the [country's] constitution. 
  Crvenkovski thanked Kooijmans for his support for Skopje's 
attempt to gain admission to the CSCE. Until now, the admission 
of the FYROM has been blocked by both Greece and Albania. 

</TEXT>

