<F P=100> GREECE </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Foreign Ministers Discuss FYROM Embargo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2102210094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1800 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2102210094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Brussels correspondent Nikolaos Belos--recorded] </F>
  [Text] European Union [EU] Commision member Hans van den 
Broek has taken the initiative to visit Skopje and Athens to 
seek a solution to the political problem. The visit to Skopje 
will take place on Wednesday [23 February] and to Athens on 
Thursday. At the same time, the European Commission today 
undertook a commitement to examine from the legal point of view 
the Greek Government's measures against Skopje [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] in order to establish 
whether there are reasons for referring the case against our 
country to the European Court. These are the two decisions made 
at noon today during the meeting of the EU foreign ministers. 
  According to the statement by Alternate Foreign Minister 
Theodhoros Pangalos, who is presiding over the council, the 
question of Greece's measures against Skopje was raised at the 
meeting by EU Commission President Jacques Delors. According to 
Mr. Pangalos, most of the countries criticized Greece both for 
the nature of the measures and the way in which they were 
adopted. Responding to questions from correspondents, the 
alternate foreign minister described the Government's decision 
as an exceptional measure of a political nature. We regret 
having to make this decision, he said. We would like to have 
good relations with this republic but tolerance -- as Mr. 
Pangalos put it -- has its limits. Mr. Pangalos further stressed 
that in the next few hours the Government will present to the EU 
Commission all the legal arguments that, in the Government's 
opinion, justify its decision. 
  Asked whether Greece had informed the member states in time, 
Mr. Pangalos said that the 11 members were briefed 
simultaneously with the announcement of the measures. Referring 
to the measures, the alternate foreign minister stressed that 
the embargo against FYROM does not include medicines, 
foodstuffs, or oil used by humanitarian institutions. 
  It is worth noting that, at his regular briefing of the 
correspondents this morning, the EU Commission spokesman said 
that the Commission understands very well that the FYROM issue 
is sensitive for the Greek Government and the sentimental 
reaction of Greek public opinion. However, as he said, the 
Commission in its capacity as guardian of the [Maastricht] 
Treaty has to examine the legal dimensions of the measures that 
the Government has taken in the light of the EU's lawful order. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

