<H3> <TI>   Government `Satisfied' With EU Ministers Meeting </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2202134094 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1230 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2202134094 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Commenting on a statement by the Luxembourg foreign 
minister that if Greek explanations of the measures against 
Skopje [The Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia--FYROM] are 
not satisfactory, the issue will end up at the European Court, 
government spokesman Evangelos Venizelos said Greece is willing 
to defend its positions to all international organizations. He 
added, however, that it is not a legal problem but a political 
one. Venizelos said the Greek Government is particularly 
satisfied with the outcome of the European foreign ministers' 
meeting because it handled the issue as a political one. 
  Venizelos said the measures continue to be implemented. 
Asked whether EU Commissioner Hans Van Den Broek will visit 
Skopje and Athens, the spokesman replied positively and added 
that his mission would be to examine the situation. The 
government spokesman said Van Den Broek will meet the Greek 
Government, which will express its well-known and clear 
positions. He said: For us, dialogue will begin when [FYROM 
President Kiro] Gligorov's government gives tangible proof of 
goodwill. 
  Asked about the community's mechanism and Van Den Broek's 
visit to Athens and Skopje, Venizelos said the Dutch 
commissioner will pay a visit in order to determine whether 
Skopje maintains the same intransigent behavior. Greece has 
adopted these measures after considering Skopje's intransigence. 
The spokesman described as absurd reports of an equal distance 
between the EU, Greece, and Skopje, because Greece is a member 
of the community and currently holds the presidency. Venizelos 
concluded: A presidency that has been praised so far. 

</TEXT>

