<F P=100> NORDIC COUNTRIES </F>
<F P=101> Sweden </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister To Visit Bosnia, Croatia, FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2202141094 Paris AFP in English 1400 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2202141094 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Stockholm, Feb 22 (AFP) -- Swedish Foreign Minister 
Margaretha af Ugglas will make official visits to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia and Macedonia [The Former Yugoslav 
Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] from March 7 to 11, a statement 
issued by the Foreign Ministry here said Tuesday [22 February]. 
  Af Ugglas is to meet with United Nations Protection Force 
(UNPROFOR) officials and Swedish troops stationed in the three 
countries after security improved over the past days, the 
ministry said, cautioning however that the visits may be put off 
if the situation got worse. 
  She is to visit Zagreb, Sarajevo and the besieged city of 
Tuzla in Bosnia as well as the Macedonian capital Skopje. 
  Sweden has 15 military observers, 100 troops, six military 
police and 25 civilian police in Croatia. 
  In Bosnia, 880 Swedes are part of a battalion from 
Scandinavian countries, with 170 stationed in Sarajevo, and in 
Macedonia 250 Swedish troops back up a 700-men battalion from 
northern Europe, according to military officials here. 

</TEXT>

