<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Protocol Signed To Build Highway With Albania </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA1902160194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1445 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1902160194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Istanbul, Feb 19 (A.A) -- Onur Kumbaracibasi, public 
works and housing minister, returned to Turkey from Sofia where 
he was attending a meeting held to discuss a highway project 
stretching from Albania to Turkey. 
  The Black Sea Economic Cooperation group is responsible for 
setting up the project. 
  Kumbaracibasi told reporters upon his return at Ankara's 
Esenboga Airport that the protocol of the project known as the 
West-East Corridor was signed on Friday [18 February], and that 
Bulgarian, Albanian, and Macedonian ministers participated to 
the meetings held in Sofia. 
  Italy is participating as observer. 
  The 1,000 kilometer-long highway, with its 500 km section 
between Istanbul and Sofia ready to use, will rescue Macedonia 
from its isolated position in the middle of the Balkans. 
  The corridor, which does not pass through Serbia or Greece, 
will be the main route connecting Albania to the Black and 
Aegean Seas. 
  The Bulgarian portion of the road will be financed by 
Turkey, 
and Sofia will have direct access to the Adriatic Sea and thence 
to western Europe. 
  Kumbaracibasi said the project was proposed by Turkey which 
is its greater supporter, adding it will be an advantage for 
countries with weak economies such as Albania and Macedonia. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-39864 </DOCNO>
