<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Statement on State of Emergency Extension </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2302081394 Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network in Turkish 
0530 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2302081394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara Turkiye Radyolari Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Council of Ministers has decided to recommend 
to the Turkish Grand National Assembly [TGNA] to extend the 
state of emergency in force in the provinces of Batman, Bingol, 
Bitlis, Diyarbakir, Hakkari, Mardin, Siirt, Sirnak, Tunceli, and 
Van for another four months, effective 19 March. The Council of 
Ministers met for approximately 90 minutes under Prime Minister 
Tansu Ciller. 
  In a statement after the meeting, Yildirim Aktuna, state 
minister and government spokesman, said that the Council 
discussed the terrorist incidents that took place over the past 
10 years and the issue of extending the state of emergency in 
force in the 10 provinces for another four months. He pointed 
out that the extensive terrorist activities that began in 1984 
increased greatly up until the end of 1991. As a result of the 
measures taken by the coalition government at the time, he said, 
terrorism began to decline in 1992. The number of terrorists 
who lost their lives between 1 January and 21 February 1992 and 
1 January and 21 February 1993 amounted to 88, while 345 lost 
their lives in the first 52 days of this year, Aktuna said, 
adding: The statistics show an increase in the number of 
operations against terrorists and in the number of terrorists 
killed or captured. This is the result of the important 
decisions made by our government in fighting terrorism. 
  Aktuna pointed out that within this framework, foreign 
support for the terrorist organization has been significantly 
reduced, mobile security forces have been trained, and 
conditions have been created for the antiterrorist struggle to 
be waged effectively under harsh winter conditions. 
  Aktuna stated that the Council of Ministers, in its 
determination to safeguard security during the coming local 
elections and to end terrorism, decided to recommend to the TGNA 
to extend the state of emergency in force in the 10 provinces by 
another four months as of 19 March. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

