<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   France Urges UN To Reopen Tuzla Airport `Immediately' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402081394 Paris AFP in English 0741 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2402081394 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Paris, Feb 24 (AFP) -- French Defence Minister 
Francois Leotard Thursday [24 February] called on the United 
Nations to act "as fast as possible" to reopen the northern 
Bosnian airport of Tuzla. 
  Tuzla airport, closed since May 1992, is surrounded by Serb 
forces who have refused to allow UN humanitarian flights into 
the Muslem-held city from where aid could be dispatched to other 
people in the northeast of the country. 
  Reopening of Tuzla airport "had to follow immediately in the 
steps of the Sarajevo operation," Leotard told France Inter 
radio station, speaking of this month's North Atlantic Treaty 
Organisation (NATO) ultimatum to force Bosnian Serbs to withdraw 
heavy weapons from around the besieged Bosnian capital. 
  "Everything has to follow up immediately on the Sarajevo 
ultimatum" even if force has to be used, the minister also said. 
  NATO has also called for the reopening of Tuzla airport, but 
so far has refrained from issuing an ultimatum to the Serbs in 
this respect. 
  The UN has indicated it hoped the airport might be opened to 
humanitarian flights in March. 

</TEXT>

