<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Goverment's Position `Watered Down' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2302150094 Rotterdam NRC HANDELSBLAD in Dutch 22 Feb 94 p 5 </F>
<F P=103> BR2302150094 </F>
<F P=104>  Rotterdam NRC HANDELSBLAD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Dutch </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "The Hague Sceptical About Bosnia </F>
Plea"] 
  [Text] The Hague, 22 Feb -- The Netherlands Government has 
watered down its position on measures to protect the population 
in the other Bosnian "safe areas." Yesterday Foreign Minister 
Kooijmans spoke of a certain form of ultimatum after the success 
in Sarajevo. He was in favor of action in Mostar, a town where 
the population is being hard pressed by the Croats. 
  This morning the Foreign Ministry spokesman said an 
ultimatum 
could be an instrument and the same strategy could be considered 
as in Sarajevo, but added that "the momentum of this moment" 
could be maintained by other measures as well, including the 
request for air support if the UN troops in Bosnia were unable 
to carry out their duties. This was approved by the Security 
Council last summer, and the NATO fighter aircraft have 
practised these duties. 
  At the Defense Ministry there are quite strong objections to 
applying the Sarajevo model elsewhere in Bosnia. In every new 
action from the air, the danger air actions pose for the ground 
troops must be considered carefully, according to military 
experts at the ministry. Moreover the heavy means of air 
support undoubtedly would lead to an escalation in the violence, 
and the UN troops on the ground would in fact have to go into 
action out of self-defense. 
  The United Nations wants 3,000 extra UN troops in Sarajevo 
to 
monitor the ultimatum. British troops have had to be partially 
withdrawn from Vitez for these duties. The British duties also 
include protecting the Belgian-Netherlands transport battalion 
and taking the lead in a possible evacuation. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

