<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Croatian Withdrawal </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302194694 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1914 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302194694 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn, Feb 23 (TANJUG) -- Croatian Foreign Minister 
Mate Granic said on Wednesday [23 February] that Croatia is 
ready to pull out its troops from the former Yugoslav republic 
of Bosnia-Herzegovina and that it has already withdrawn 600 
soldiers in the past few days. 
  Granic met in Bonn with his German counterpart Klaus Kinkel 
to discuss the involvement of Croatia's regular army troops in 
the fighting between the Bosnian Croats and Muslems in Mostar, a 
city in southern Bosnia, and in other regions. 
  The UN Security Council has ordered Croatia to withdraw its 
troops from Bosnia by February 17 or face international 
sanctions. After the deadline expired, the UN secreatry general 
informed the Security Council that about 5,000 soldiers of the 
regular Croat Army remain in Bosnia. 
  Following talks with Granic, Kinkel said there are hopes for 
a peaceful solution to the war in Bosnia especially after the 
favourable developments in Sarajevo, but he underscored that 
there are `several Sarajevos' in Bosnia. 
  In an interview with the German radio Kinkel said that 
Russia's involvement in the peace process in Bosnia is extremely 
important and that there can be no resolution of the crisis in 
the former Yugoslavia without Russia. 
  Granic told a press conference that the Croatian Government 
would do everything so that the problems in Bosnia and in the 
other parts of the former Yugoslavia are resolved in a peaceful 
way through political means. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

