<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kinkel Comments </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302122694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1116 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302122694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN)--German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel 
does not rule out new threats by NATO with the aim of achieving 
further demilitarization in Bosnia-Herzegovina following the 
peace brought about in Sarajevo. After talks with Mate Granic, 
his Croatian counterpart, Kinkel told journalists in Bonn today 
that it is now important to increase efforts to find a political 
solution to end the civil war. The prerequisites for this are 
good. Granic pointed out the negotiations taking place between 
the Croatians and the Muslim Bosnians in Zagreb today. 
  Kinkel emphasized that "Sarajevo" had been "a first small, 
but very important step." Now they will, as if working on a 
mosaic, try to bring peace to the other main crisis areas in the 
conflict. It is important to open Tuzla Airport. It must be 
possible to transport humanitarian aid to the people in the 
disputed areas. 
  The foreign minister announced he would be explaining the 
overall situation in the former Yugoslavia to the cabinet on 
Thursday [24 February]. A "new momentum" has entered the 
negotiations over the past few days that must be exploited. He 
also spoke to Granic about the repatriation problem regarding 
Croat refugees in Germany. Both sides are interested in a joint 
solution. 

</TEXT>

