<H3> <TI>   Kinkel, Ukraine's Slepichev Discuss Economic Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202145694 Berlin DDP/ADN in German 1404 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202145694 </F>
<F P=104>  Berlin DDP/ADN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Bonn (DDP/ADN) -- Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel has 
promised Ukraine further German support to help develop the 
country's economy. Kinkel met Anatoliy Zlenko, his Ukrainian 
counterpart, in Bonn today. Oleh Slepichev, Ukrainian minister 
of external economic relations, and Ukrainian Health Minister 
Yuriy Spizhenko also attended the meeting. 
  Following talks that lasted more than two hours, Kinkel told 
journalists that the country, with its 53 million inhabitants, 
has considerable economic problems. Germany also wants to help 
within the scope of the European Union. Kinkel also stressed 
that Ukraine must be included in the new European security 
structure. 
  Zlenko acknowledged Germany's willingness to support the 
process of economic reform in Ukraine. The country remains on 
the economic reform course. In order to continue these reforms, 
it needs the support of partners, he said. 
  Earlier, he handed a letter from Ukrainian President Leonid 
Kravchuk to Chancellor Helmut Kohl. The letter contained 
specific requests for help, Zlenko added. He announced that 
Kravchuk will visit Germany soon. 

</TEXT>

