<F P=100> GERMANY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Economic Development Assessed `With More Restraint' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU1702134394 Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU in German 
17 Feb 94 p 11 </F>

<F P=103> AU1702134394 </F>
<F P=104>  Frankfurt/Main FRANKFURTER RUNDSCHAU </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> German </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["ptz"-signed report: "Rexrodt Admits Setback at the End of </F>
the Year"] 
  [Text] Bonn -- The FRG Economics Ministry currently 
assesses the economic development with more restraint than a few 
weeks ago. "Around the end of the year," the economic 
development "did not show a unified picture; however, the basic 
economic trend seems to go generally upward," Rexrodt's ministry 
now notes. 
  The economists in Bonn are more worried about the situation 
in the west German industry. "Orders received and production 
once again declined there during the fourth quarter, following 
an upswing that was observed during the third quarter." All in 
all, the adjusted GDP, as a comprehensive expression of the 
overall economic performance, "may have declined a bit" during 
the last quarter of 1993. As a positive element, the ministry 
notes "improved" business expectations in the processing 
industry. 
  On 21 January, the ministry said: "The slow climb out of the 
deep valley of the economic development had already begun in the 
old laender last year. During the second and third quarter, the 
GDP increased slightly and probably stayed at the achieved level 
also during the last quarter of 1993." 

</TEXT>

