<F P=100> FRANCE </F>
<H3> <TI>   Government Approves Reactivation of Superphenix Reactor </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BR2302150694 Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS in French 23 Feb 94 
p 4 </F>

<F P=103> BR2302150694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris LE QUOTIDIEN DE PARIS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> French </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Superphenix To Be Reactivated for </F>
Research Purposes"] 
  [Text] Yesterday, the government decided to reactivate the 
Superphenix fast breeder reactor, which "will no longer be 
operated as a nuclear power station, but will become a reactor 
reserved for research and demonstration purposes." 
  "The reactor will develop as rapidly as possible toward 
subgeneration [sous-generation] so as to limit the quantities of 
plutonium produced," added the press release issued by the 
offices of Prime Minister Edouard Balladur, which also set forth 
several conditions relating to security. 
  The Superphenix, which will now become "a research 
prototype" 
and no longer function as "an industrial power station," will be 
reactivated after the successful completion of the work aimed at 
combating the fires caused by sodium leaks, after a phased 
start-up procedure, and on condition that the production of 
electricity is no longer a prime objective. 
  Moreover, the offices of the prime minister stressed that by 
virtue of its being a prototype, the functioning of the 
Superphenix could be suspended. In an effort to explain this 
decision to reactivate the Superphenix, they stress its 
importance for research into long-life radioactive waste 
reduction. In its press release, the government also stressed 
that the reactor would be integrated "into efforts to master 
nuclear technologies," with the "two main objectives being 
research on the utilization of plutonium (...) and the reduction 
of long-life radioactive waste produced by reprocessing fuel 
from nuclear reactors." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-39945 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu037_j_94003" </HT>


