<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Observer, Mikhailidhis Discuss CBM's </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2302143894 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2302143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Serge Abou, the European Union [EU] observer on the 
Cyprus issue, said that the signing of an agreement between the 
two communities on the confidence-building measures [CBM's] 
would be a significant achievement. Abou also noted that such 
an agreement would create the correct impetus, as he put it, for 
achieving an overall Cyprus solution. 
  In a statement after his meeting with Foreign Minister 
Alekos 
Mikhailidhis this morning, Abou described the contacts he had 
with President Glavkos Kliridhis and Gustave Feissel [the UN 
secretary general's alternate special representative in Cyprus] 
as very important in view of the report on the Cyprus issue, 
which he will start preparing for the EU's Council of Ministers. 
  Asked if the CBM's are compatible with EU norms, Abou said 
the United Nations has assured him that there is no problem. 
But, he added, there is no easy answer to this issue. 
Answering another question on Turkey's stance, he noted that 
during his recent visit to Turkey, he received assurances that 
Turkey supports the CBM's. 
  Foreign Minister Alekos Mikhailidhis said in his statement 
that the government will assist the observer in his task in 
every way. He added: The government's goal is to explain to the 
EU observer the government position on how the various 
approaches toward a Cyprus solution are linked with Cyprus' 
efforts for accession to the EU. 
  Abou completed his orientation visit and left Cyprus this 
afternoon. 

</TEXT>

