<F P=100> CYPRUS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Comments Talks in Germany </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2302142694 Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network in Greek 1130 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2302142694 </F>
<F P=104>  Nicosia Cyprus Broadcasting Corporation Radio 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Greek </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government does not intend to turn the 
residents of Famagusta who will return to the fenced-off area 
into an enclave. For this reason, the government is expecting 
answers to the vitally important questions of safety and access 
to Famagusta. This statement was made by Foreign Minister 
Alekos Mikhailidhis, who added that next week the course of 
discussions on the implementation of the confidence-building 
measures [CBM's] will be determined. 
  Mr. Mikhailidhis was addressing a news conference this 
morning on the results of his contacts in Germany and said that 
the prospects for the CBM's are not favorable right now. He 
also stressed that, if the Turkish side's intransigence and 
filibustering tactics continue, the whole course will be 
reexamined. Mr. Mikhailidhis further emphasized that the Greek 
Cypriot side should be particularly careful so as to be 
convincing about the Turkish intransigence and pointed out that 
the discussions on the CBM's will have repercussions on Cyprus' 
efforts for accession to the European Union [EU]. Referring to 
these efforts, Mr. Mikhailidhis said that the next goal set by 
the government is setting a date for opening official EU-Cyprus 
negotiations on the island's accession. This goal, he added, 
will be pursued during the Greek presidency of the EU. Mr. 
Mikhailidhis also expressed satisfaction over his contacts with 
German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel who, he said, supported 
Cyprus' accession to the EU. 

</TEXT>

