<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-057 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Demirel Discounts Coup </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2302160394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1515 GMT 23 Feb 93 </F>
<F P=103> TA2302160394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb.23 (A.A) -- President Suleyman Demirel 
said today the regime of Turkey was fully erect with all its 
institutions and "fabrication of conspiracy and coup theories is 
extremely unsuitable. And if Turkey is facing certain 
difficulties at present, this is because of the coups it had 
underwent." 
  Speaking to the press after a ceremony, President Demirel 
said "let the democratic institutions, its army, and people of 
the country alone." 
  "Everything is being discussed at parliament. A government 
which has received a vote of confidence is on duty, whether you 
like it or not. An independent court system is in effect. The 
press is free and on duty. I am serving the country as the 
president elected by this country's parliament." 
  "We might have certain problems but who doesn't?" 
  "I am making a call to everyone, since there are debates on 
whether a coup will be made in Turkey," he said. 
  "I am addressing everyone. The regime is functioning in 
Turkey. Here I am representing democracy and national 
sovereignty and advise everyone to mind their own business." 
  Asked if a statement made a day before by Deputy Premier 
Murat Karayalcin that a coup might occur in Turkey has a special 
importance, President Demirel said, "I am not going to interpret 
words said by someone else. You should listen to what people 
have said before and after. There is no meaning in isolating 
the word coup from the whole statement." 
  In May 27, 1960 a coup has been made by the Turkish Army and 
the premier and his two friends have been executed. In March 
12, 1971 another coup took place. The third coup of the Army was 
made on September 12, 1980. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-39971 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drweu057_q_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-WEU-94-057 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> TURKEY </F>
<H3> <TI>   DEP Leader Warns Against `Playing With Fire' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2302173394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1545 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2302173394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, Feb.23 (A.A) -- Leader of Democracy Party 
(DEP) Hatip Dicle said today that, those who are acting against 
his party were in fact playing with fire in the Kurdish question. 
  Addressing his party's consultation meeting here, Dicle said 
that Turkey was passing through its most comprehensive economic 
and political crisis in its 70-year-long history. 
  He recalled that the European Parliament had decided to send 
observers to southeastern Turkey during the March local polls 
and "this decision is a political victory of our party won 
against the policy of a state." 
  Dicle claimed that his party's deputies were the ones who 
were facing the removal of their immunity and "we are not afraid 
from such a thing because we are a party of a cause." 
  "We defend the brotherhood of peoples under any condition. 
We are not the ones who brought the country to this situation. 
Attempts to play with fire in the Kurdish question is very 
dangerous. We invite everyone to common sense [as received]," 
he said. 
  The party's deputy from Adiyaman, Mahmut Kilinc, answering 
questions of reporters during the meeting said that their party 
was "against the violence of the PKK and the state." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

