<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Fruitful' Granic-Andreatta Meeting Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302204194 Zagreb HTV Television in Serbo-Croatian 1830 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302204194 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb HTV Television </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] At a cordial and constructive meeting with 
Italian Foreign Minister Andreatta, Mate Granic was told that 
Italy is willing to help in the process of seeking solutions. 
Minister Andreatta -- who is very familiar with the situation 
-- expressed satisfaction with the fact that Italy is involved. 
He told Minister Granic that Italy has a great deal of 
understanding for Croatia's position. The talks resulted in the 
realization that relations between Croatia and Italy are being 
advanced to a great extent and that Italy can exercise a 
positive influence in the process of seeking solutions. The two 
ministers talked extensively over a working lunch. The Croatian 
side assesses the talks as cordial and very fruitful. 
  Minister Granic and Ambassadors Rudolf and Livljanic talked 
early this evening with Monsignor Jean-Louis Tauran, the 
Vatican's state secretary. The sixth meeting between the two 
politicians took place in a very cordial atmosphere. The Holy 
See is following developments on the ground with great interest 
as well as the diplomatic process for resolving the crisis. It 
is paying particular attention to the agreement between Generals 
Roso and Delic. In the Vatican there are reports that this 
agreement has a good chance of success. 
  The Holy See reiterated its opinion that a solution to the 
crisis should certainly be found, and also that agreement should 
be reached between the Croats and Muslims. The pope will be 
informed about the talks. Minister Granic has handed over 
President Tudjman's message to the pope. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

