<F P=100> ITALY &amp; VATICAN CITY </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatia's Granic Stresses Croat-Muslim Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302223494 Zagreb Radio Croatia Network in Serbo-Croatian 
2100 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302223494 </F>
<F P=104>  Zagreb Radio Croatia Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Serbo-Croatian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report from Rome by Silvije Tomasevic, SLOBODNA DALMACIJA </F>
correspondent, for Croatian radio] 
  [Text] The NATO ultimatum to the Bosnian Serbs has been an 
absolute success, and now the question arises of how to prevent 
further conflicts in Bosnia-Herzegovina and resume peace 
negotiations, Croatian Minister of Foreign Affairs Mate Granic 
told us this afternoon following his talks with Italian Minister 
of Foreign Affairs Andreatta and the Holy See State Secretary 
Jean- Louis Tauran. It has been concluded that the key to peace 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina can be found through the Croat-Muslim 
agreement [as heard]. Americans, Germans, and Italians are 
involved in the search for that key. 
  Minister Granic told us that he came to Rome today in order 
to clarify the Croatian standpoint regarding the creation of a 
Croat-Muslim federation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. There are some 
differences as regards the set-up of the future 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. However, Granic told us that the Croatian 
position was met with understanding by the Italian side. 
Croatia's view of Italy's importance in the negotiations is 
positive, Granic told us. 
  In reference to his talks with Tauran, he said that the Holy 
See assessed as positive the fact that Croatia has accepted the 
Vatican's suggestions. 

</TEXT>

