<H3> <TI>   India Urges Vote Against Pakistan's Human Rights Resolution </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2402101794 Delhi All India Radio Network in English 0830 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2402101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Delhi All India Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Geneva, India has urged friendly countries at the 
ongoing session of the UN Human Rights Commission to give up 
their neutral stance on the Kashmir issue and come out openly 
against Pakistan's state-sponsored terrorism in Jammu and 
Kashmir. The minister of state for external affairs, Mr. Salman 
Khurshid, told the heads of various delegations in informal 
meetings in Geneva that abstaining in the event of a voting on 
the Pakistan-proposed resolution on Kashmir will undermine the 
very concept of human rights and will encourage Islamabad's 
involvement in terrorism. Talking to Indian reporters, Mr. 
Khurshid said New Delhi expects a categorical rejection of the 
resolution. 

</TEXT>

