<F P=100> INTER-EUROPEAN AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   EU Warns Against Changes in GATT Tariff Cut Offers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2402171194 Paris AFP in English 1633 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2402171194 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, Feb 24 (AFP) -- GATT tariff-cutting offers 
made by the European Union on Wednesday [23 February] are 
conditional upon other countries sticking to their tariff 
commitments, an EU spokesman warned here Thursday. 
  EU officials said only 22 of 116 countries involved in the 
Uruguay Round of GATT trade talks had submitted their final 
tariff-cutting offers, which were supposed to reach the GATT 
secretariat by February 15. 
  Member countries of the General Agreement on Tariffs and 
Trade agreed last December 15 on the principle of significant 
cuts in import tariffs under the Uruguay Round, which is due to 
be signed formally in Marrakesh on April 15. 
  The GATT members were supposed to translate their general 
tariff-cutting commitments into detailed product-by-product 
reductions. The EU has done so but many other countries have not. 
  The EU spokesman said: "Our offers are based on the 
condition 
that the offers of the other parties are not diminished from 
what was approved on December 15 in Geneva." 
  EU officials say they are worried by Washington's apparent 
intention to reduce U.S. offers -- notably for utility vehicles, 
electronics and non-ferrous metals -- in reprisal against 
Japan's refusal to increase imports of U.S. goods. 
  They have warned that the Union might reduce its own tariff 
offers if it is disadvantaged by any shrinking in cuts offered 
by other countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

