<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Turkish Foreign Minister Cetin Begins Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2402083294 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 2000 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2402083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin at The Hague as Dutch 
Foreign Minister Peter Kooijmans' official guest has started his 
official meetings. 
  TRT correspondent Ihsan Gunal reports from The Hague: 
  [Begin recording] The issue most emphasized during Cetin's 
meetings in The Hague is Bosnia-Herzegovina. Cetin started his 
visit by meeting with Dutch Prime Minister Ruud Lubbers. 
  Answering reporters' questions following the meeting, Cetin 
said that Turkey's request to send close to 10,000 soldiers to 
Bosnia-Herzegovina is still valid adding that the necessary 
directives regarding the initiatives were issued to NATO and the 
United Nations. Cetin pointed out that he had sent letters 
regarding the issue to the secretary generals of the NATO and 
the United Nations as well as to the foreign ministers of some 
countries. 
  Later, official meetings headed by the two foreign ministers 
started. The issue most emphasized in the agenda is 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. Focusing on the terrorism issue, bilateral 
relations, economic relations, the situation of the Turks living 
in Europe, xenophobia, Turkey's membership in the European 
Union, and the situation in the Caucasus were also discussed. 
  Cetin will conclude his contacts in The Hague tomorrow. [end 
recording] 

</TEXT>

