<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Bosnia, FYROM </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2402123794 Ankara TRT Television Network in Turkish 2200 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2402123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara TRT Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Turkish </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report over video] </F>
  [Text] Turkish Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin has stated 
that other countries should not be concerned by Turkey's 
interest in sending troops to Bosnia-Herzegovina. Cetin, at The 
Hague as the official guest of the Dutch Foreign Minister Peter 
Kooijmans, concluded todays' contacts. 
  TRT correspondent Ihsan Gunal reports from The Hague: 
  [Begin recording] Following the official meetings, Cetin 
answered reporters' questions and said that Turkey wants to send 
troops to Bosnia-Herzegovina in order to have peace established 
there as soon as possible. Indicating that there are rumors as 
to Turkish troops should not be sent because one of the parties 
in Bosnia-Herzegovina might object, Cetin pointed out that in 
spite of the Bosnians' objections, certain countries' troops are 
still being sent to the region, noting that this constitutes a 
double standard. Stressing that Holland also shares Turkey's 
views on this issue, Cetin indicated that the Dutch believe that 
fresh military forces are needed in Bosnia-Herzegovina and that 
they should be reinforced. 
  Cetin also explained that during the official meetings he 
briefed the Dutch delegation on the terrorism and human rights 
issue in Turkey. Stating that the Netherlands -- in keeping 
with its legislation -- cannot ban terrorist organizations, 
Cetin added that nevertheless it will continue to prohibit 
terrorist activities adding that the Netherlands finds Turkey's 
fight against terrorism justified. 
  In answer to a reporter's question, Cetin explained that 
Greece's closing the Thessaloniki port to Macedonia [The Former 
Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia -- FYROM] exacerbates the crisis 
in the Balkans. Stressing that this move should not have been 
perpetrated, Cetin said that, if necessary, Turkey will extend 
all kinds of help to the FYROM via Varna. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

