<F P=100> BENELUX </F>
<F P=101> Netherlands </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cetin Speaks at Luncheon </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2502054194 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1600 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2502054194 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The Hague (AA) -- Foreign Minister Hikmet Cetin on 
Thursday [24 February] said that the presence of any foreign 
organization's observers during the coming local elections in 
Turkey is unnacceptable, adding Turkey is a democratic country 
and anyone can come and observe as an individual. 
  He was speaking at a luncheon he hosted in honour of his 
counterpart, Peter Kooijmans, at the Turkish Embassy in The 
Hague. 
  After the luncheon, Cetin met with members of the Foreign 
Ministry commission of the Netherlands' parliament. 
  Speaking to reporters after the meeting, Cetin said his 
contacts in The Hague have been very constructive, adding talks 
focused on terrorism, the sitaution in Bosnia-Herzegovina and 
economic relations. 
  On terrorism Cetin said that it is the international 
responsability of all countries not to support terrorist 
organizations, adding the NATO and UN resolutions necessitate 
this. 
  Cetin also said that the Turkish citizens living in Turkey 
[as received] will be able to vote during the local elections. 

</TEXT>

